>
  <p>
    This section is written explicitly for the professional — the wealth advisor, trust officer, family office director, or fiduciary who has encountered situations in their practice where a client's behavioral health intersects with their financial wellbeing, and who has recognized that their training did not prepare them for these moments.
  </p>

  <p>
    These are not edge cases. They are among the most consequential and most frequent challenges in wealth advisory practice. The client whose substance use is eroding the family's financial foundation. The beneficiary whose mental health challenges affect their capacity to manage distributions. The family patriarch whose cognitive decline is obvious to everyone except the patriarch himself. The trusted client who calls not about their portfolio but about their child's arrest, their spouse's psychiatric hospitalization, or their own struggle with a condition they have never discussed with anyone.
  </p>

  <h2>The Training Gap</h2>

  <p>
    The wealth advisory profession has historically maintained a clear boundary between financial matters and personal matters. Advisors are trained in portfolio construction, tax strategy, estate planning, and fiduciary law. They are not trained in recognizing substance use disorders, navigating conversations about mental health, understanding the clinical treatment landscape, or coordinating the multidisciplinary teams that complex family situations demand.
  </p>

  <p>
    This boundary served the profession well in an era when the advisor's role was narrowly defined and the client's expectations were limited to financial performance. That era is ending. Today's clients — particularly those in the rising generation — expect their advisors to understand the whole of their circumstances. They expect advisors who can engage with behavioral health topics with the same competence they bring to investment analysis. They expect trusted professionals who can coordinate across domains rather than retreating behind the boundary of professional scope.
  </p>

  <p>
    The articles in this section provide the frameworks, vocabularies, and practical resources that advisors need to meet these expectations without exceeding their competence or compromising their professional obligations.
  </p>

  <h2>The Fiduciary Standard in Practice</h2>

  <p>
    The fiduciary standard requires advisors to act in their clients' best interests. In practice, this standard creates obligations that extend well beyond financial optimization when a client's behavioral health is affecting their financial wellbeing or decision-making capacity. The fiduciary who ignores a client's substance use because it falls outside the traditional scope of advisory work is not fulfilling their fiduciary obligation — they are avoiding it.
  </p>

  <p>
    This does not mean that fiduciaries should become clinicians. It means they should understand enough about the clinical landscape to make informed decisions, recognize warning signs, ask appropriate questions, and coordinate with specialists when situations require expertise beyond their own. The fiduciary standard, properly understood, demands not clinical competence but clinical awareness.
  </p>

  <h2>Conversations That Define Careers</h2>

  <p>
    The most valuable skill an advisor can develop in this domain is the ability to have conversations that most professionals avoid entirely. How do you raise concerns about a client's substance use? How do you discuss cognitive decline with a family that is not ready to acknowledge it? How do you respond when a client asks for help with a situation that exceeds everything you were trained for?
  </p>

  <p>
    These conversations define careers. The advisor who handles them with competence and sensitivity earns a level of trust that no financial performance can replicate. The advisor who avoids them — or handles them poorly — risks losing not only the relationship but the opportunity to provide the most meaningful service of their professional life.
  </p>

  <h2>Building the Right Team</h2>

  <p>
    Complex family situations require multidisciplinary teams — clinical providers, legal counsel, crisis communicators, family therapists, and specialists whose expertise the advisor may never have needed before. Building, coordinating, and managing these teams is a skill unto itself, and it is a skill that no advisory training program teaches.
  </p>

  <p>
    The articles below address the full spectrum of the advisor's practice at this intersection — from the foundational principles of fiduciary duty to the practical challenges of coordinating care teams, navigating ethical dilemmas, and maintaining trusted relationships across generational transitions. They are written by and for professionals who recognize that the most consequential work in wealth advisory happens not in portfolio reviews but in the moments when a client's life and their wealth intersect in ways that demand something more than financial expertise.
  </p>
